    [
        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• “Some of you created shapes that have names, such\nas 'square' or 'rectangle.' Some of you created\nshapes or designs that do not have names. We can\ncall these shapes ‘figures’ as we talk about them. This\nword will be helpful in describing other shapes that\ndon’t have names.”\n• Invite previously selected students to share how they\nordered their figures.\n• As students share, consider asking, “How did you\ndecide how much space each figure covered?”\n• “It is common to use squares, such as the square\ntiles we used in this activity, to measure area. Each\nsquare tile is one square unit of area. If we count the\nnumber of tiles that make up a figure, we can find\nthe area of the figure. For example, if a figure is\ncovered by 12 square tiles, it has an area of 12\nsquare units.”", line(204)),
        context_item("Activity 2 — Activity Synthesis", "• Display the first, fourth, and fifth figures.\n• “How did you tile each figure?” (I filled the whole\nfigure with tiles until I couldn’t fit any more. I started\n\nwith the bottom row, then made the row above it\nuntil the figure was full.)\n• “How did you determine the area of each figure?” (I\ncounted the number of tiles it took to fill each figure\ncompletely.)\n• Consider asking, “Which figures did you and your\npartner think had the easiest areas to find?” (The\nrectangle, because there were clear rows and\ncolumns. The third figure, because we could split it\ninto 2 rectangles. All of them, because they could all\nbe covered completely with square tiles and had no\nuncovered space.)\n• “Why was it important not to leave any gaps as you\ntiled your figures?” (Because the whole figure needs\nto be completely covered. If there are gaps between\ntiles or around the edge, then the whole figure isn’t\ncovered.)", line(294)),
