    [
        context_item("Warm-up — Activity Synthesis", "• “Why do 100 and 200 show up in both of these\ncounts?” (We say 100 and 200 when we're counting\nby tens or hundreds. We can think of 100 as 10 tens\nand 200 as 20 tens. 100 and 200 are multiples of 10\nand multiples of 100.)", line(110)),
        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• Select previously identified students to share their\nresponses.\n• “Kiran and Priya are correct. There isn’t one closest\nmultiple of 10 to 415 because it’s right in the middle\nof two multiples of 10. There isn’t one closest\nmultiple of 100 to 750 because it’s right in the middle\nof two multiples of 100.”\n• “In cases such as this, we round up. For example,\nsince 415 is halfway between 410 and 420, we round\nup to 420 when rounding to the nearest ten.”\n\n• “Since 750 is halfway between 700 and 800,\n\nwe round up to 800.”\n• ”In both situations, we could go the other way, but it\nis helpful if we all do the same thing.”", line(209)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "“Today we rounded numbers to the nearest ten and the nearest hundred.”\n\n“What important ideas about rounding did we learn today?” (Rounding to the nearest ten and the nearest hundred\nsometimes gives the same number. When a number is right in between two multiples of 10, or two multiples of 100, we\nround up. We can round to estimate. How we round can change our estimate.)", line(350))
    ],
    source('knowledge/geometry/corpus/im_teacher_guides/grade3/unit3/lesson15.md')).

compiled_lesson_context('IM-G3-U3-L16',
