    [
        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• “How did the unit container help us compare the\nvolume of water it took to fill both of the containers?”\n(We can count how many units it took to fill each\ncontainer. Then we compared them.)\n• “We saw that the volume of a container is the\namount of liquid it takes to completely fill a\n\ncontainer.”\n\n• “We can say that the volume of Container A is ___\nunits because it takes __ units of water to fill it up.”\n• “We can say that the volume of Container B is __ units\nbecause it takes __ units of water to fill it up.”\n\n.", line(221)),
        context_item("Activity 2 — Activity Synthesis", "• “How would we label the marks to show the number\nof liters each mark shows?” (We would label the\nbottom mark with 1, then the one above it with 2,\n\nand keep labeling up to the top mark. The bottom of\nthe container would be 0 liters.)\nLabel the marks with numbers.\n“How is the bottom of the container like the edge of a\nruler?” (They both show zero. The bottom of the\ncontainer is like the 0 mark on a ruler.)\n“Liters can be abbreviated with an uppercase L. We\ncould show that each number represents a number\nof liters by writing an uppercase L next to each\nnumber.”\nWrite “L” next to each number on the container that\nwas marked and labeled.\n“We can say that the volume of the water in the\ncontainer is __ liters.”\n“We can also say the volume of the container is\nabout __ liters.”\n“What are some other containers you’ve seen that\nalso have a volume of about __ liters?” (a large sink,\na storage bin, a large jug of water, a bucket, a small\ntrash can)", line(341)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "“Today, we learned about the volume of a liquid and the volume of a container.”\n\n“How would you describe the volume of a liquid to someone who doesn't know what it is?” (Liquid volume is the amount\nof space that a liquid takes up. It’s like measuring how much water is in a glass.)\n\n“How would you describe the volume of a container to someone who doesn’t know what it is?” (The volume of a\ncontainer is how much liquid is needed to fill it up. It’s like how much liquid something could hold without overflowing.)\n\n“Have you seen containers that were labeled with the volume of liquid they contain? Can you give some examples?”\n(bottles of drinks or oil, jugs of detergent or liquid soap)", line(376))
    ],
    source('knowledge/geometry/corpus/im_teacher_guides/grade3/unit6/lesson7.md')).

