        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• “How can you tell if your answers are correct? How\ncan you check them?” (One way to check the result of\nsubtraction is by adding it back to the number being\n\nsubtracted. One way to check the result of addition is\nby subtracting one addend from the sum. Another\nway of checking is by performing the calculations\nwith the numbers written in expanded form.)", line(183)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "Display these subtraction problems.\n\nA                                                               B\n\nAsk students to decide if they agree with the following statements, without doing any calculations. Students should be\nprepared to defend their decisions.\n\n• “Only Problem A can be done. Problem B cannot be completed because the 8s in the second number are greater\nthan most digits in the first number.” (Disagree)\n• “Problem A doesn’t require any decomposing.” (Agree)\n• “Problem B requires decomposing units in four places.” (Disagree)\n• “The result of the subtraction in A is in the hundred-thousands.” (Agree)\n• “The result of the subtraction in B is also in the hundred-thousands” (Disagree)\nIf time permits, ask students to find each difference (Problem A is 143,210 and Problem B is 98,766) and to show a way\nto check their answers.", line(304))
