        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "Invite students to share how they reasoned about the height of each stone tower. Ask others if they reached the same\nconclusions but reasoned differently, or if they reached different conclusions.\n\n“One clue says that Tyler’s tower is 5 times as tall as the shortest tower. We know that Tyler’s tower is 4 feet 2 inches. Is it\neasier to find the height of the shortest tower using 4 feet 2 inches or using 50 inches? Why?” (The first uses two\ndifferent units, so we’d have to divide 4 feet by 5 and 2 inches by 5, or think about what number multiplied by 5 gives 4\nand 2. If we use inches, we’re dealing with one number that is clearly a multiple of 5.)\n\n“How did you decide whether Elena’s tower is greater than 6 feet? Did you convert the 6 feet into inches, convert Diego’s\ntower into feet, or do something else?”\n\nRecord strategies. Highlight that while it is often helpful to express a larger unit in terms of a small unit, some problems\ncan be reasoned without doing so.", line(352))
    ],
    source('knowledge/geometry/corpus/im_teacher_guides/grade4/unit5/lesson15.md')).

