        context_item("Activity 1 — Student Task Statement", "How many different rectangles can be made, using\nthe entire length of one 12-inch chenille stem?\n\n1. Record as many pairs of side lengths as you\ncan think of.\n\nlength          width\n\n(inches)       (inches)\n\n2. Which pair of measurements represents the\nside lengths of a square?", line(166)),
        context_item("Activity 2 — Student Task Statement", "1. Your teacher will assign a pair of side lengths\nto you. Use a chenille stem to build a rectangle\nwith those side lengths.\nWhat is the perimeter of the rectangle?\n\n2. Two 12-inch chenille stems are joined end to\nend (with no overlaps) and used to build a\nsquare.\n\na. What is the side length of this square?\nWhat is its perimeter?\nb. How do the side length and the perimeter\nof this square compare to those of the first\n\nsquare?\n\n3. Several chenille stems are joined end to end\n(with no overlaps) to build a square with a\nperimeter of 60 inches.\n\na. How many chenille stems are used?\nExplain or show how you know.\n\nb. What is the side length of the square?\n\nc. How do the side length and the perimeter\n\ncompare to those of the first square?", line(267)),
        context_item("Activity 3 — Student Task Statement", "1. Draw the following rectangles on centimeter\ngrid paper. Label each rectangle. Record the\nside lengths and the perimeter of each.\n◦ Rectangle A has a perimeter of 16\n\ncentimeters.\n\n◦ Rectangle B has side lengths that are 3\ntimes the side lengths of Rectangle A.\n\n◦ Rectangle C has side lengths that are      o\nthe side lengths of B.\n\nlength     width    perimeter\nrectangle\n(cm)      (cm)       (cm)\n\nA                                   16\n\nB\n\nC\n\n2. Rectangle D has a perimeter of 96 centimeters.\nThe perimeter of D is:\n\n◦ __________ times the perimeter of A\n\n◦ __________ times the perimeter of B\n\n◦ __________ times the perimeter of C", line(368)),
