    [
        context_item("Warm-up — Activity Synthesis", "• “How do the first three expressions help you find the\n\nvalue of the last expression?”", line(108)),
        context_item("Activity 2 — Activity Synthesis", "• Invite students to share their responses to the last\n\ntwo problems and their reasoning.\n\n• “How did you know that 5 chenille stems were used\n\nin the last problem?” (60 is 5 times 12.)\n\n• “How did you know that the side length of the last\n\nsquare is 15 inches?” (The perimeter of a square is 4\ntimes its side length.           )\n\n• Consider displaying a table as shown here to\n\nhighlight the relationships between the number of\n\nchenille stems used, the perimeter of the square,\nand the side length of the square.\n\nnumber of       perimeter       side length of\nchenille stems     (inches)      square (inches)\n\n1              12                 3\n\n2              24                 6\n\n5              60                15", line(299)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "Invite previously selected students to share their drawings and completed table from the last activity. Display drawings\nand tables for all to see.\n\n“How did you find the perimeters for Rectangles B and C?” (I doubled the length and doubled the width, and then added\nthose two numbers. I added the length and width and then multiplied the sum by 2. I added up all the side lengths.)\n\nIf time permits, consider asking:\n\n“What do you notice about the relationships between Rectangles A, B, and C in these tables and drawings?” (The\nperimeters are 16, 48, and 24 cm in all responses. The measurements of Rectangle B are 3 times those of A and 2 times\nthe measurements of C.)\n\nSelect other students to share their responses to the last question about Rectangle D.\n\n“How did you figure out how the perimeter for D compares to those of A, B, and C?” (I tried to find out what times 16\ngives 96, what times 48 gives 96, and what times 24 gives 96.)", line(442))
    ],
    source('knowledge/geometry/corpus/im_teacher_guides/grade4/unit5/lesson16.md')).

