    [
        context_item("Warm-up — Activity Synthesis", "• “For Images A, C, and D, how does each\nrepresentation show an unknown?”\n\n• “What is the unknown in each representation?\nExplain how you know.”\n• Record student responses.\n\n• Consider asking students to create a situation that\ncan be described by these representations.", line(100)),
        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• Invite previously selected students to share their\nrepresentations and their reasoning for problem 1.\n• “How does ______’s diagram or expressions relate to\nthe problem?” (The diagram and the expressions\nshowed       and 8 times as much.)\n• “How was solving this problem like the second\nproblem? How is it different?” (The question, the\nnumbers, and multiplicative comparison “8 times as\nmuch” were the same in both problems. The diagram\nfrom the first problem could also work with the\nsecond problem. The calculations were different\nbecause of what the problems were about.)\n• “How were both of these problems different from\nother problems we solved in this unit?” (We had to do\nmore than one calculation to solve the problem.)\n• “Both problems asked for the amount of total sales\n\nand involved multiplying and adding. How did you\nknow which operation to use and with which\nnumbers?” (One problem involves adding first, and\nthen using multiplicative comparison to find the\namount of total sales. In the other problem,\nmultiplicative comparison is first, and then you add\nto find the amount of total sales for the day. It’s\nimportant to pay attention to the information given\nin the problem and the multiplicative comparisons.)", line(217)),
        context_item("Activity 2 — Activity Synthesis", "• Invite previously selected students to share their\ndiagrams or equations.\n• “How does __'s diagrams or equations match the\nstory problem?”\n• “Why might someone choose to show their work with\nequations instead of drawing diagrams for this\nparticular problem?”\n• “What did you learn about paying attention to what\nthe question is asking?”\n• If time, invite previously selected students to share\nhow they revised their thinking.\n◦ “What did you notice during the partner\ndiscussion and how did you change your work\nafter noticing it?”\n◦ Consider asking a different student to rephrase\nthis revision in their own words.", line(316)),
