        context_item("Warm-up — Activity Synthesis", "• Some students may notice that it is handy to think in\nterms of         because it would mean dealing with\nmultiples of 90 rather than with multiples of 45.\nHighlight their explanations.\n• If no students decomposed expressions such as\n,       , and        into sums of        and\n, discuss how this could be done. (See Sample\nResponses.)", line(110)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "“Today we used     angles and a protractor to measure the size of an angle.”\n\n“What do you know about a         angle?” (It’s     of a full turn of a ray through a circle. It's a small angle compared to the\nother angles we have seen. It’s        of a half turn of a ray through a circle, like on a protractor.)\n\n“How can    angles tell us the sizes of other angles?” (It’s a smaller angle, so we can use it to be more precise when we\nmeasure or compare angles. We can count or find the number of            angles in an angle to find its measurement.)\n\n“How would we know how many            angles are in another angle?” (We can use a protractor, which is marked with 180 or\n360 one-degree angles.)\n\nDisplay:\n\n“We saw that a protractorhas two sets of numbers. How do you know which set of numbers to use when measuring an\nangle?” (Either set could be used, but it is easier to use the set that counts up from 0 rather than counts back from 180.)\n\n“Take 1–2 minutes to add any new words from today’s lesson to your word wall. Share your new entries with a neighbor\nand add any new ideas you learn from your conversation.”", line(364))
