    [
        context_item("Warm-up — Activity Synthesis", "• “These are both diagrams of baseball fields. The\n\nfigure on the left is a diagram of Fenway Park in\n\nBoston, Massachusetts. The figure on the right is a\ndiagram of Dodger Stadium in Los Angeles,\nCalifornia.”\n• “Fenway Park does not have a symmetrical baseball\nfield, but Dodger Stadium does. Take a moment to\ndraw the line of symmetry for the field in Dodger\nStadium.”\n\n• 30 seconds: quiet work time\n\n• “In baseball, the fields don’t have to be symmetrical\n\nbecause the teams take turns hitting and fielding on\nthe same field. So, neither team has an advantage.”\n• “What are some sports that always have symmetrical\nfields or courts?” (Soccer, football, basketball, tennis,\nhockey)\n\n• Share responses and record for all to see. Keep\ndisplayed for the next activity.", line(104)),
        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• Invite groups to share the sport they chose and how\nit would change if the field or court wasn’t\nsymmetrical.", line(190)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "“Today, we designed sports fields with no lines of symmetry and developed new rules for playing on the fields or courts\nyou designed.”\n\n“What were some decisions you made about your design? How did the decisions you made affect the rules you created\nfor your design?” (We decided to make one side of the field shorter than the other side. This caused us to make a rule\nabout switching sides more often so the game would be fair. We decided to make one side of the field narrower, which\nmade it harder to score. We adjusted the scoring at the narrow side so scores were worth more points.)\n\nConsider having students respond to the previous question as a journal prompt.", line(322))
