        context_item("Activity 2 — Activity Synthesis", "• Invite students to share their calculations for\nDelaware.\n• “Is Delaware close in size to the garbage patch? How\ndo you know?” (No, it is not close at all. 1,600,000\nsquare kilometers is a lot more than 7,392 square\nkilometers.)\n• “Is the garbage patch greater than or less than 10\ntimes as large as Delaware?” (Much greater, because\nthat’s only about 70,000 square kilometers, which is\nway less than a million.)\n\n• “Is the garbage patch greater than or less than 100\ntimes as large as Delaware?” (Greater, because that’s\nabout 700,000 square kilometers, and the garbage\npatch is more than double that.)\n• “How could you estimate the area of New\nMexico?”(596 is close to 600, which is a nice number.\n552 is harder, but if I say that’s about 500, then I get\nan estimate of               or 300,000.)\n• “How did you decide which area to circle on the\n\nmap?”(5 New Mexicos would make about 1,600,000\n\nsquare kilometers, so I circled New Mexico and 4\n\nother states close in size to it.)", line(303)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "“Today we looked at the Great Pacific Garbage Patch which has an area of about 1,600,000 square kilometers. We saw\nhow big that is by comparing it to different states.”\n\n“If the Great Pacific Garbage Patch was a rectangle, what could be its side lengths?” (It could be 1,600,000 kilometers by\n1 kilometer but 1,600,000 kilometers is too long. It could be 1,250 kilometers by 1,250 kilometers. I could multiply one of\nthe lengths of New Mexico by 5, so it could be about 3,000 kilometers by 550 kilometers.)\n\n“Much of the garbage in the Great Pacific Garbage Patch is plastic. Tomorrow we will investigate the amount of\nrecyclable plastic we produce each year.”", line(341))
    ],
    source('knowledge/geometry/corpus/im_teacher_guides/grade5/unit4/lesson18.md')).

