        context_item("Activity 1 — Activity Synthesis", "• Invite students who wrote a number in their\nrepresentation to share. Ask, “how many?” questions\nthat are answered by those numbers. For example, if\na student counted boats in the beach math story\npicture, ask:\n• “How many boats did they count? How do you\nknow?” (They counted 5 boats. I know because they\nwrote the number 5.)\n• “We can write numbers to show how many things we\ncounted. If you haven’t already, write a number to\nshow how many you counted.”\n• “When you play Math Stories during centers, be sure\nto write a number to show how many things you\ncounted. You can also use drawings or words.\"", line(182)),
        context_item("Activity 2 — Activity Synthesis", "• Display a bag containing 8 objects labeled with the\nnumber 8.\n• “How many objects do you think are in this bag?\nWhat makes you think that?” (I think there are 8\nobjects in the bag, because the number 8 is on the\nsticky note.)\n• 30 seconds: quiet think time\n• Share responses.\n• “Let’s see if you were right.”\n• Take the objects out of the bag and count them.\n• “There were 8 objects in the bag. We could tell\nbecause the number 8 was written on the bag. Now\nI’m going to put the objects in a line. How many\nobjects are there now?”\n• Demonstrate moving the 8 objects into a line.\n• “We still have 8 objects. I didn’t add any more objects\nor take any away, so there are still 8 objects.”", line(295)),
        context_item("Lesson Synthesis", "“Why are numbers helpful?” (They tell us how many. It is quicker to write a number than to draw a picture or take out\nobjects.)\n\nIf needed, say: “We can write numbers to tell how many there are. Numbers help us communicate ‘how many’ easily.”\n\n“Let’s practice counting to 20.”\n\nDemonstrate counting to 20. Count to 20 as a class 1–2 times.\n\nKindergarten                                     CC BY NC 2024", line(379))
